<P>
AIDS-STRICKEN GIRL ENTERS SCHOOL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TAMPA, Fla. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A mentally disabled, AIDS-stricken 7-year-old stepped into a classroom for the 
first time in her life today, with bows in her hair, a knapsack on her back and 
the cheers of supporters surrounding her. 
</P>
<P>
Her adoptive mother, Rosa Martinez, who fought a 2 1/2-year court battle 
against school officials who feared a health risk and had required that the 
girl be confined to a glass isolation booth, called today the most important 
day in her daughter Eliana's life. 
</P>
<P>
Supporters cheered as mother and daughter walked into the one-story, red-brick 
Manhattan Exceptional Center, where 201 students are enrolled. Eliana's teacher 
said many pupils hugged the girl when she came into their classroom. 
</P>
<P>
Martinez is a nurse who adopted Eliana as an infant in her native Puerto Rico. 
Eliana was stricken with AIDS after receiving transfusions of tainted blood 
shortly after her premature birth. 
</P>
