<HEADLINE>
<P>
P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
U.S. IMPORT PRICES CLIMB 1.7% 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The prices Americans pay for imported goods rose 1.7% during the first three 
months of 1989, down slightly from the pace in the previous quarter, the 
government reported today. 
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department said the first-quarter rise followed a 2% increase in the 
final three months of last year and a 1.3% decline during the third quarter of 
1988. 
</P>
<P>
The January-March increase was primarily due to an 18.3% jump in prices for 
imported fuels, led by a 27.8% surge in prices for imported crude oil in 
response to a November agreement by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting 
Countries. 
</P>
<P>
Excluding fuels, import prices rose a modest 0.5% during the first quarter 
after climbing 2.4% in the previous quarter. The advance in prices for 
non-energy imports was held down in part by the appreciation of the U.S. dollar 
during the period, the Labor Department said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
