<HEADLINE>
<P>
S.F. COURTROOM PACKED; 
</P>
<P>
CANSECO PLEADS INNOCENT TO TWO WEAPONS CHARGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Injured Oakland Athletics superstar Jose Canseco pleaded innocent to a pair of 
weapons charges today before a packed courtroom filled with fans, city office 
workers and celebrity watchers. 
</P>
<P>
Canseco, dressed in a beige suit, quietly answered Judge David A. Garcia, who 
released the American League slugger on his own recognizance over the protest 
of the district attorney's office. The judge ordered a June 8 preliminary 
hearing on the charges. 
</P>
<P>
The judge drew chuckles from the gallery with his comments that Canseco should 
not have any problem making any future court appearances despite the fact that 
"I understand he occasionally is out of this jurisdiction for business reasons. 
I have heard he's even been as far away as Toronto on occasion." 
</P>
<P>
Canseco was arrested April 21 by UC San Francisco campus police after a 
passer-by saw a pistol on the floor of his cherry-red Jaguar in the medical 
center parking lot. Canseco was at the facility having his injured wrist 
X-rayed. 
</P>
<P>
Robert Shapiro, Canseco's Los Angeles-based attorney, said his client was 
carrying the gun because of telephone threats to Canseco and his wife. He said 
Canseco also did not know he was on a university campus at the time of the 
arrest. 
</P>
<P>
"He has been getting threatening phone calls for two to three weeks," Shapiro 
said. "People are calling, breathing heavily, using obscene language and saying 
other things. This happens to people who are in the light as Mr. Canseco is, 
and he's scared." 
</P>
<P>
Canseco, who signed autographs while awaiting his turn in court, was greeted by 
cheers and clapping as he left the courtroom. However, he did not speak to 
reporters because his attorney claimed the A's slugger had a wisdom tooth 
removed Wednesday night and had not slept. 
</P>
<P>
Shapiro said the 1988 American League MVP is very much distressed by the case. 
</P>
<P>
"He wants it to be resolved as quickly as possible," Shapiro said. "He wants 
his public image to be as good as his image on the baseball field." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Jose Canseco signs autographs before Municipal Court hearing. Associated 
Press 
</P>
